ion drive can do when you plug its numbers into the<br>
 equations.<br>
Ke = m (v*v) /2 for 1 kilogram of mass * efficiency of <br>
the ion engine which is about 99%<br>
For 1 gram of mass devide above figures by 1000<br>
for 1 milligram of mass devide above figures by 1,000,000<br>
for 1 microgram of mass devide above figures by 1,000,000,000.<br>
Thrust = exchaust velocity v* ion beam mass measured<br>
in kilograms.<br>
1 newton = force to acclerate 1 kg of mass at 1/10 g<br>
which is 1 meter per second.<br>
<br>
The acceleration rate in terms of G for ion rocket<br>
= thrust/mass * G(10m/sec) <br>
1 mole of any ion propellant  contains 6.02 * 10 23rd power ions in it.<br>
The  atomic weight of the ion determines how many grams of mass 1 mole of it contains.<br>
Example: 1 mole of Hyrogen ions is 6.02 * 10 the 23rd<br>
power protons which has a mass of 1 gram .<br>
1 mole of nitrogen 14 is 6.02 * 23 power<br>
nitrogen 14 ions which has a mass of 14 grams <br>
<br>
The velocity attained by an ion when it is accelerated in<br>
an electric field is calculated as follows:<br>
Ve =  2 * the sqaure root of Q/M * Va (accelerating voltage)<br>
Q = charge of the individual ion in volts<br>
M = the mass of a single ion in kilograms.<br>
1 single proton or neutrom has a mass of 1 * 10 to the -27 power kilograms<br>
1 proton has a  charge of  1.6 * 10 the -19 power electron volts.<br>
If an ion has 100 protons in its nucleous its charge would <br>
be 1.6 * 10 -17 power electron volts.<br>
Va is the net accelerating voltage used in ion motor.<br>
If I have an ion motor with one acclerating electrode or <br>
1 screen  Va = the  voltage on in in electron volts.<br>
If i have two screens in which 1 is -1000 volts and the other<br>
screen is - 101,000 volts then Va= 100,000.<br>
If I have a linear ion  accelerator that has (100) <br>
-1,000,000 volt screens in a line to acclerate the ions <br>
then Va = - 100,000,000 volts.<br>
